osition":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":34,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The black and the red normal curves have means or centers at ","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"key":"AISuxgFux8"},{"type":"inlineMath","value":"\\mu","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"html":"<span class=\"katex\"><span class=\"katex-mathml\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><semantics><mrow><mi>μ</mi></mrow><annotation encoding=\"application/x-tex\">\\mu</annotation></semantics></math></span><span class=\"katex-html\" aria-hidden=\"true\"><span class=\"base\"><span class=\"strut\" style=\"height:0.625em;vertical-align:-0.1944em;\"></span><span class=\"mord mathnormal\">μ</span></span></span></span>","key":"bHlrM29Bqd"},{"type":"text","value":" = 10. However, the red curve is more spread out and thus has a larger standard deviation. As you look at these two normal curves, notice that\nas\nthe red graph is squished down, the spread gets\nlarger, thus allowing the area under the curve to remain the same.","position":{"start":{"line":31,"column":1},"end":{"line":31,"column":1}},"key":"mhj8px0XVm"}],"key":"cJaWj0AHkl"}],"key":"QvVOv1cPam"},{"type":"listItem","spread":true,"position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":45,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"paragraph","children":[{"type":"text","value":"The black and the green normal curves have the same standard deviation or spread (the range of\nthe black\ncurve\nis\n6.5-13.5,\nand\nthe green\ncurve’s\nrange is\n10.5-17.5).","position":{"start":{"line":35,"column":1},"end":{"line":35,"column":1}},"key":"upzMxsfe9s"}],"key":"JNdVKlZ7DC"}],"key":"Goy70R8x5h"}],"key":"yNfy0ktE3v"},{"type":"paragraph","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"children":[{"type":"text","value":"Even more important than the fact that many variables themselves follow the normal curve is the role played by the normal curve in sampling theory, as we’ll see in the next module of probability. Understanding the normal distribution is an important step in the direction of our overall goal, which is to relate sample means or proportions to population means or proportions. The goal of this section is to better understand normal random variables and their distributions.","position":{"start":{"line":46,"column":1},"end":{"line":46,"column":1}},"key":"YVwYmG1pwo"}],"key":"KXboF2C7Ba"}],"key":"CCBuE3P4hh"}],"key":"ddskRjNlml"},"references":{"cite":{"order":[],"data":{}}},"footer":{"navigation":{"prev":{"title":"Probability Distribution (2 of 2)","url":"/pages/m11-probability-distribution-2-of-2","group":"Unit 4: Probability"},"next":{"title":"Introduction to Normal Random Variables(2 of 3)","url":"/pages/m11-introduction-to-normal-random-variables2-of-3","group":"Unit 4: Probability"}}},"domain":"http://localhost:3002"}